<paragraph id="3D7697363547FFD0FEF7FE14666CFDFA" blockId="43.[264,1323,284,790]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
Distribution (
<tableCitation id="704BA28D3547FFD0FE19FE146512FE22" box="[470,571,484,510]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="9.[264,343,851,872]" captionText="TABLE 1. Distribution of Afroestricus species by country." pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Tables 1</tableCitation>
, 
<tableCitation id="704BA28D3547FFD0FD82FE146577FE22" box="[589,606,484,510]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="10.[264,343,563,584]" captionText="TABLE 2. Phenology of Afroestricus species. Abbreviations refer to the months of the year." pageId="43" pageNumber="44">2</tableCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="A5F28BB33547FFD0FDA2FE1465FCFE22" box="[621,725,484,510]" captionStart="FIGURE 194" captionStartId="70.[264,357,1870,1891]" captionTargetBox="[459,1150,1206,1854]" captionTargetId="figure-93@70.[411,1177,1171,1869]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURE 194. Distribution of six species of Afroestricus in Africa and Madagascar." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5050679" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5050679/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 194</figureCitation>
). Collected in northern 
<collectingCountry id="45DED7A63547FFD0FC3DFE146356FE22" box="[1010,1151,484,510]" name="Madagascar" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
from April to June.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3D7697363547FFD0FEF7FDC466B5FCCA" blockId="43.[264,1323,284,790]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
Remarks. 
<taxonomicName id="FAC9ECB53547FFD0FE7EFDC46594FD91" box="[433,701,564,589]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persuasus">
<emphasis id="0FBD4B243547FFD0FE7EFDC46594FD91" box="[433,701,564,589]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Afroestricus persuasus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from congeners by the yellow fore coxa, characters in the key and distinctive terminalia (
<figureCitation id="A5F28BB33547FFD0FC49FDAC631AFDAA" box="[902,1075,604,630]" captionStart="FIGURES 101–110" captionStartId="42.[264,370,1555,1576]" captionTargetBox="[306,1289,291,1532]" captionTargetId="figure-99@42.[282,1306,272,1551]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURES 101–110. Afroestricus persuasus (Oldroyd). Male terminalia: 101–103. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views. 104. Gonostylus. 105–106. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Female terminalia: 107–108. Dorsal and ventral views. 109. Spermatheca. 110. Genital fork." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5050649" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5050649/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Figs. 101–110</figureCitation>
). The male is further recognized by the swollen hind femur and the numerous, close­spaced, posteroventral bristles on basal 1/3 of the hind femur which are bordered dorsally by abundant, short, black setae. Presently, 
<taxonomicName id="FAC9ECB53547FFD0FDFEFD2465F8FD31" box="[561,721,724,749]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persuasus">
<emphasis id="0FBD4B243547FFD0FDFEFD2465F8FD31" box="[561,721,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">A. persuasus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only known species of 
<taxonomicName id="FAC9ECB53547FFD0FBBBFD24622BFD31" authorityName="Scarbrough Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[1140,1282,724,749]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0FBD4B243547FFD0FBBBFD24622BFD31" box="[1140,1282,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Afroestricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry id="45DED7A63547FFD0FEC7FD0C66B1FCCA" box="[264,408,764,790]" name="Madagascar" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
